      <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
      <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
      <p>How intrinsic value shifts when we adjust our mathematically derived growth and discount rates.</p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="sensitivity-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
              {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
                <th class={Math.abs(g - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
              ))}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
              <tr>
                <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
                {row.values.map((v, i) => (
                  <td class={Math.abs(row.dr - discountRate) < 0.001 && Math.abs(sensitivityGrowth[i] - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>
                    ${v}
                  </td>
                ))}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- ═══ RISKS & FAQ ═══ -->
      <h2>Risks & What the Model Misses</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Commodity Inflation:</strong> Cocoa and sugar prices are notoriously volatile. Extreme spikes compress margins if Mondelez cannot pass costs to consumers fast enough.</li>
        <li><strong>Consumer Trade-Down:</strong> In sustained inflationary environments, consumers may swap premium Cadbury or Oreo products for private-label generic alternatives.</li>
        <li><strong>GLP-1 Drugs:</strong> The rise of weight-loss drugs (Ozempic/Wegovy) poses a long-term behavioral risk to snack consumption volumes.</li>
        <li><strong>Currency Exposure:</strong> As a global enterprise, a remarkably strong US Dollar negatively impacts reported international earnings.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Why use a Two-Stage DCF for a snack company?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">While snacks aren't hyper-growth software, Mondelez still exhibits a period of near-term pricing power and volume recovery (Phase 1) before settling into perpetual, GDP-like maturity (Phase 2).</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>Where did the 10Y Treasury yield come from?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">The 10-Year Treasury yield is set at a fixed 4.18% as a proxy for the baseline risk-free rate of return, acting as the foundation for the WACC.</div>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How is Net Cash calculated?</summary>
          <div class="faq-answer">Net Cash is calculated by subtracting Total Debt from Cash & Equivalents, dynamically fetched from Mondelez's most recent balance sheet. A negative number indicates net debt.</div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </>
